{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475346"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:32:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12641"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.03,0.56,0.21,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49082"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5122"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34116"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1472"},{"type":"tags","id":"1870"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49082"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-week-old premature neonate with a birth weight of 900 g is admitted to the neonatal intensive care unit with a clinical presentation of tachypnoea, poor feeding, and a continuous murmur on auscultation. Physical examination reveals decreased breath sounds and a prolonged expiratory phase. The infant was born to a mother with a history of multiple risk factors during pregnancy, including poorly controlled maternal diabetes, uncontrolled maternal hypertension, and smoking during pregnancy. In addition, the mother was over 35 years of age at the time of delivery. The infant undergoes an echocardiogram which shows left-to-right shunting of blood between the aorta and the pulmonary artery, with a peak velocity of 2.5 m/s and a left atrium-to-aorta ratio of 1.5, indicating the presence of a significant left-to-right shunt.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following risk factors is most likely directly responsible for this infant\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Maternal diabetes","Maternal hypertension","Prematurity","Smoking during pregnancy","Maternal age over 35 years"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe echocardiographic findings in this neonate indicate left-to-right shunting of blood between the aorta and the pulmonary artery, with a peak velocity of 2.5 m/s and a left atrium-to-aorta ratio of 1.5, indicating the presence of a significant left-to-right shunt. These findings suggest the possibility of PDA, which may be confirmed by further diagnostic testing. \u003Cstrong\u003EPrematurity\u003C/strong\u003E with a birth weight of less than 1 kg is a well-established risk factor for PDA, as the ductus arteriosus normally closes shortly after birth but may remain open in premature infants. Infants born before 37 weeks of gestation are more likely to have PDA than full-term infants. Other risk factors for PDA in premature infants may include respiratory distress syndrome, necrotising enterocolitis, and mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoorly controlled maternal diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E can increase the risk of fetal macrosomia, congenital heart defects, and other complications during pregnancy. These complications may indirectly contribute to the development of PDA, as the fetus may be under stress and experience changes in blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncontrolled maternal hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E can increase the risk of fetal growth restriction, premature birth, and other complications during pregnancy. These complications may indirectly contribute to the development of PDA, as the fetus may be under stress and experience changes in blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmoking during pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E can increase the risk of premature birth, low birth weight, and other complications during pregnancy. These complications may indirectly contribute to the development of PDA, as the fetus may be under stress and experience changes in blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal age over 35 years\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with an increased risk of PDA. Advanced maternal age may be associated with an increased risk of chromosomal abnormalities and other complications during pregnancy, such as gestational diabetes and preeclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Prematurity with a birth weight of less than 1kg is a major risk factor for the development of PDA."],"references":["Gillam-Krakauer M, Mahajan K. Patent Ductus Arteriosus. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430758/","Qu XY, Zhou XF, Qu Y, Tang BZ, Mu DZ. [Risk factors for patent ductus arteriosus in neonates]. Zhongguo Dang Dai Er Ke Za Zhi. 2011 May;13(5):388-91. Chinese. PMID: 21575344."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34116"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34116"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-23T15:51:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-23T15:51:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5122"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","link